At its most basic level, computer security is about ensuring that systems and software are only accessed by authorized users. That idea has been sitting at the core of everything I’ve been working on, even on quieter days like today where real-life commitments took priority.

Alongside the technical side, there’s also been a personal shift. I’ve been focusing on becoming more disciplined, cutting out habits that don’t help, and trying to move away from who I was toward who I want to be. It’s not instant, but it feels like a worthwhile process.

On the development side, I spent time refactoring parts of the Security_Demo_Web_App, excluding the C++ backend for now due to missing SQL libraries on this machine. I also revisited several utilities, improving the Python version of PortPeep, creating a PowerShell version which still needs testing, and building a C++ version as well. SysNyAdminEnny.cpp and Sila.cpp both received updates, with general improvements in structure and usability.

Overall, nothing major in terms of output today, but solid groundwork for what comes next.

[16/01/2026]

This week has been more focused on refining existing tools and laying the groundwork for future CVE-related work.

Addison.py has been reworked into a modular structure, which should make it far more maintainable and flexible moving forward. Alongside that, the shell version of PortPeep has been improved. While the shell script is neat in its own way, the Python and C++ implementations remain more practical for most use cases.

I’ve also been revisiting older security concepts from a purely educational standpoint. Historically, certain attack techniques involving de-authentication and WPS exploitation were effective against poorly configured networks. These approaches relied heavily on timing and specific device behavior, and while they were once widely applicable, modern hardware and firmware have significantly improved in how they respond to such conditions.

Anything in that space today should be approached strictly within controlled and legal environments, such as personal lab setups, as the landscape has changed considerably over time.


